      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get the concept, but how does the attacker actually trick the device into connecting to them instead of the real router? do they do something specific to the signal or the handshake process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the attacker can trick the device into connecting to them by manipulating the Wi-Fi signal or the handshake process. Here's a simple explanation: when you connect to a Wi-Fi network, your device and the router exchange a secret handshake, called a handshake protocol, to establish a secure connection. The attacker can set up a fake Wi-Fi network with a name (SSID) that looks just like the real one. When you connect to this fake network, your device thinks it's connecting to the real router, but it's actually connecting to the attacker's router. The attacker can then intercept the data being sent between your device and the website, just like the goblin intercepting your secret message in the marketplace. This is how they can trick your device into connecting to them instead of the real router. To avoid this, always look for the network name and password on a physical sign or ask the staff, and avoid connecting to public Wi-Fi networks without a VPN.",
